Task #2

Tibble and Graph

continent max_GDP min_GDP
Africa 21951.21 241.1659
Americas 42951.65 1201.6372
Asia 113523.13 331.0000
Europe 49357.19 973.5332
Oceania 34435.37 10039.5956

Explanation

The tibble is a tabular representation of the minimum and maximum GDP per Capita for each continent in the gapminder dataset. The boxplot shows the minimum and maximum but also provides additional useful information such as median GDP per capita for each continent as well as the 1st quartile (25th percentile) and 3rd quartile (75th percentile) for GDP per capita for each continent. The boxplot also clearly shows outliers.As can be seen from the plot, Oceania has the highest median GDP per capita while Africa has the lowest. Asia has the greatest spread of GDP per capita values while Oceania has the least.

Task #3

Tibble of the Mean and Standard Deviation per Continent

gapminder %>%
  group_by(continent) %>%
  summarize(Mean=mean(gdpPercap), StandardDev=sd(gdpPercap))%>%
  knitr::kable()
continent Mean StandardDev
Africa 2193.755 2827.930
Americas 7136.110 6396.764
Asia 7902.150 14045.373
Europe 14469.476 9355.213
Oceania 18621.609 6358.983

Histogram of Spread of the GDP Per Capita Per Continent

ggplot(gapminder, aes(gdpPercap))+facet_wrap(~ continent, nrow=4, scales="free_y") +
  geom_histogram(bins = 50)+ggtitle("Histograms of GDP Per Capita Per Continent ") + xlab("GDP Per Capita")+scale_x_continuous(labels=scales::dollar_format())+ylab("Frequency")

Density Diagram of the GDP Per Capita Per Continent

ggplot(gapminder, aes(gdpPercap))+facet_wrap(~ continent, nrow=4, scales="free_y") +
  geom_density()+ggtitle("Density Diagram of GDP Per Capita Per Continent ") + xlab("GDP Per Capita")+scale_x_continuous(labels=scales::dollar_format())+ylab("Frequency")

Explanation

The tibble shows the mean and the Standard Deviation of the GDP per Capita for each continent. The histograms show the spread of the GDP per Capita values for each continent. From the histograms we can see that Asia has the largest spread of GDP per capita values while Africa has the smallest spread. In addition, we can see that the values for Africa are left-skewed. Asia has a significant right-tail as do the Americas meaning that their distribution is skewed to the right. The density diagram complements the histogram by better demonstrating the shape of distribution of the data. For example, density plots allow to more easily determine whether the data follows a normal distribution or is skewed.

Task #4

Tibble of Weighted (by population) Mean Life Expectancy per year

min_life_exp<-gapminder %>%
  group_by(year)%>%
  summarise( 
            lifeExp_weighted_mean = weighted.mean(lifeExp,pop)) 
  knitr::kable(min_life_exp)
year lifeExp_weighted_mean

1987 64.41635

Bar Graph of Weighted (by population) Mean Life Expectancy per year

min_life_exp %>%
ggplot(aes(x=year,y=lifeExp_weighted_mean))+geom_col()+xlab("Year")+ylab("Weighted Mean Life Expectancy")+ ggtitle("Weighted Mean Life Expetancy Per Year")

Explanation

The tibble shows the mean life expectancy per year when weighted by population. The bar graph shows that the trend is towards an increase in the mean weighted life expectancy over the years of the gapminder data set.
